> Äá»ƒ duyá»‡t cÃ¢y BST theo thá»© tá»± `giáº£m dáº§n`, ta chá»‰ cáº§n Ä‘áº£o ngÆ°á»£c thá»© tá»± cá»§a >In-order thÃ´ng thÆ°á»ng, tá»©c lÃ : `Right â†’ Node â†’ Left`

# **CODE**

- Trong bÃ i `notebook` nÃ y, mÃ¬nh sáº½ tiáº¿n hÃ nh **xÃ¢y dá»±ng láº¡i cáº¥u trÃºc `Binary Search Tree` tá»« Ä‘áº§u** `(from scratch)` báº±ng ngÃ´n ngá»¯ **Python** mÃ  khÃ´ng sá»­ dá»¥ng báº¥t ká»³ thÆ° viá»‡n há»— trá»£ sáºµn nÃ o.
- Má»—i hÃ m trong Ä‘oáº¡n code Ä‘á»u Ä‘Æ°á»£c **comment giáº£i thÃ­ch chi tiáº¿t** Ä‘á»ƒ giÃºp cÃ¡c báº¡n dá»… dÃ ng theo dÃµi vÃ  hiá»ƒu Ä‘Æ°á»£c chá»©c nÄƒng cá»§a tá»«ng pháº§n.


> ğŸ’¬ **LÆ°u Ã½**:  
> VÃ¬ kiáº¿n thá»©c cÃ²n háº¡n cháº¿, bÃ i viáº¿t nÃ y mang tÃ­nh cháº¥t **tham kháº£o**. Náº¿u cÃ³ Ä‘iá»u gÃ¬ thiáº¿u sÃ³t hoáº·c chÆ°a há»£p lÃ½, mÃ¬nh ráº¥t mong nháº­n Ä‘Æ°á»£c sá»± gÃ³p Ã½ tá»« má»i ngÆ°á»i Ä‘á»ƒ hoÃ n thiá»‡n hÆ¡n.  
> **Xin chÃ¢n thÃ nh cáº£m Æ¡n!** ğŸ˜ŒğŸ˜ŒğŸ˜Œ

```python
class Node:
  def __init__(self, val):

```


```python
class BinarySearchTree:
  # HÃ m khá»Ÿi táº¡o
  def __init__(self):
    self.__root = None

  # Chá»©c nÄƒng thÃªm
  def __add(self, val: int , root: None) -> Node:
    new_node = Node(val)
    # Náº¿u Node hiá»‡n táº¡i lÃ  None -> Node trÆ°á»›c nÃ³ lÃ  Node cáº§n thÃªm
    if root is None:
      return new_node
    else:
      # TÃ¬m nhÃ¡nh cÃ³ Node phÃ¹ há»£p Ä‘á»ƒ thÃªm
      if new_node.val > root.val:
        root.right = self.__add(val, root.right)
      else:
        root.left = self.__add(val, root.left)

    return root

  # HÃ m tÃ¬m Node nhá» nháº¥t bÃªn nhÃ¡nh pháº£i
  def __find_Smallest_Right(self, root: Node) -> Node:
    # Náº¿u khÃ´ng cÃ³ Node bÃªn trÃ¡i ná»¯a thÃ¬ nÃ³ chÃ­nh lÃ  Node trÃ¡i cuá»‘i cÃ¹ng
    if root.left is None:
      return root
    else:
    # Tiáº¿p tá»¥c tÃ¬m kiáº¿m
      return self.__find_Smallest_Right(root.left)

  # Chá»©c nÄƒng xÃ³a
  def __delete(self, val: int , root: Node) -> Node:
    if root is None:
      return root

    # TÃ¬m nhÃ¡nh phÃ¹ há»£p chá»©a Node cáº§n xÃ³a
    if val > root.val:
      root.right = self.__delete(val, root.right)
      return root

    if val < root.val:
      root.left = self.__delete(val, root.left)
      return root

    # Node hiá»‡n táº¡i lÃ  Node cáº§n xÃ³a
    if val == root.val:
      # TrÆ°á»ng há»£p khÃ´ng cÃ³ node lÃ¡
       if root.right is None and  root.left is None:
          return None

      # TrÆ°á»ng há»£p cÃ³ má»™t node lÃ¡
       if root.right is None:
          return root.left
       if root.left is None:
          return root.right

      # TrÆ°á»ng há»£p cÃ³ 2 node lÃ¡
       smallest_right = self.__find_Smallest_Right(root.right)
       root.val = smallest_right.val
       root.right = self.__delete(smallest_right.val, root.right)
       return root

  # Chá»©c nÄƒng duyá»‡t máº£ng In-order
  def __inverse(self, root: Node) -> None:
    if root is None:
      return None

    self.__inverse(root.left)
    print(f"{root.val} ")
    self.__inverse(root.right)


  # Chá»©c nÄƒng tÃ¬m
  def __search(self, root: Node, val: int) -> bool:
    if root is None:
      return False

    if root.val == val:
      return True

    if val > root.val:
      return self.__search(root.right, val)

    return self.__search(root.left, val)

  ### CÃ¡c hÃ m dÆ°á»›i Ä‘Ã¢y má»›i Ä‘Æ°á»£c ngÆ°á»i dÃ¹ng sá»­ dá»¥ng trÃ¡nh ngÆ°á»i dÃ¹ng biáº¿t
  ### Ä‘Æ°á»£c nÃ³ hoáº¡t Ä‘á»™ng cá»§a code theo OOP (tÃ­nh Ä‘Ã³ng gÃ³i)

  def add(self, val: int) -> None:
    self.root = self.__add(val,self.__root)


  def delete(self, val: int) -> None:
    self.root = self.__delete(val, self.__root)


  def inverse(self) -> None:
    self.__inverse(self.__root)

  def search(self, val: int) -> bool:
    return self.__search(self.__root, val)
```

## [Video tham kháº£o](https://leetcode.com/problems/same-tree/description/)  **`EASY`**

Given the roots of two binary trees p and q, write a function to check if they are the same or not.

Two binary trees are considered the same if they are structurally identical, and the nodes have the same value.


```python
### Äá»‘i vá»›i cÃ¡c bÃ i toÃ n dáº¡ng cÃ¢y nÃ³i chung, chÃºng ta khÃ´ng thá»ƒ sá»­ dá»¥ng máº£ng nhÆ° trong link list Ä‘Æ°á»£c
### giáº£ sá»­ ta cÃ³ 2 cÃ¢y nhÆ° sau [1 ,2] vÃ  [1 ,null ,2] khi Ä‘Æ°a nÃ³ vÃ o máº£ng cáº£ 2 Ä‘á»u sáº½ lÃ  arr = [1,2] nhÆ°ng thá»±c táº¿
### chÃºng lÃ  2 cÃ¢y khÃ¡c nhau má»™t cÃ¢y giÃ¡ trá»‹ 2 á»Ÿ nhÃ¡nh trÃ¡i, cÃ²n cÃ¢y cÃ²n láº¡i thi 2 náº±m á»Ÿ nhÃ¡nh pháº£i do Ä‘Ã³
### sá»­ dá»¥ng máº£ng lÃ  má»™t cÃ¡ch tiáº¿p cáº­n sai. ChÃºng ta cáº§n cÃ³ hÆ°á»›ng tiáº¿p cáº­n nÃ³ Binary Search Tree hÆ¡n


### Trong bÃ i toÃ¡n nÃ y, ta sáº½ dÃ¹ng cÃ¡c thuáº­t toÃ¡n duyá»‡t (inverse) Ä‘á»ƒ giáº£i quyáº¿t, má»—i láº§n duyá»‡t ta sáº½ kiá»…m tra xem
### giÃ¡ trá»‹ cá»§a p.val == q.val hay khÃ´ng, náº¿u khÃ´ng tráº£ vá» False cho Ä‘áº¿n khi háº¿t cÃ¢y


class TreeNode:
    def __init__(self, val=0, left=None, right=None):
        self.val = val
        self.left = left
        self.right = right

class Solution:
    # HÃ m duyá»‡t theo pre-order
    def inverse(self, p, q) -> bool:
        # Náº¿u cáº£ 2 Ä‘á»u duyá»‡t háº¿t mÃ  khÃ´ng cÃ³ gÃ¬ xáº£y ra thÃ¬ return True
        if p is None and q is None:
            return True

        # Má»™t bÃªn null má»™t bÃªn khÃ´ng cÃ³ -> cÃ³ sá»± khÃ¡c nhau
        if p is None or q is None:
            return False

        # 2 giÃ¡ trá»‹ trá»‹ láº¡i khÃ¡c nhau trong vá»‹ trÃ­ node khÃ¡c nhau
        if p.val != q.val:
            return False

        # Kiá»…m tra nhÃ¡nh trÃ¡i vÃ  pháº£i cá»§a nÃ³
        left = self.inverse(p.left, q.left)
        right = self.inverse(p.right, q.right)

        return left and right

    def isSameTree(self, p: Optional[TreeNode], q: Optional[TreeNode]) -> bool:
        return self.inverse(p, q)
```

## [Video tham kháº£o](https://leetcode.com/problems/delete-node-in-a-bst/description/)  **`MEDIUM`**

Given a root node reference of a BST and a key, delete the node with the given key in the BST. Return the root node reference (possibly updated) of the BST.

Basically, the deletion can be divided into two stages:

1. Search for a node to remove.
2. If the node is found, delete the node.


```python
### Äá»‘i vá»›i bÃ i nÃ y thi ta Ä‘Ã£ cÃ³ cÃ¡ch giáº£i náº±m trong pháº§n CODE cá»§a tÃ´i rá»“i ğŸ«£ğŸ«£ğŸ«£
### nÃªn chá»‰ cáº§n khai triá»…n láº¡i theo Ä‘Ãºng format cá»§a Leetcode thÃ´i

class TreeNode:
    def __init__(self, val=0, left=None, right=None):
        self.val = val
        self.left = left
        self.right = right


class Solution:
    # HÃ m tÃ¬m con pháº£i bÃ© nháº¥t (successor)
    def FindSmallestRight(self,root):
        if root.left is None:
            return root
        return self.FindSmallestRight(root.left)

    # HÃ m xÃ³a
    def deleteNode(self, root: Optional[TreeNode], key: int) -> Optional[TreeNode]:
        # Náº¿u duyá»‡t Ä‘áº¿n háº¿t root mÃ  khÃ´ng tÃ¬m Ä‘Æ°á»£c node cáº§n xÃ³a hoáº·c root ban Ä‘áº§u lÃ  rá»—ng thÃ¬ tráº£ vá» None luÃ´n
        if not root:
            return None

        # Äang kiá»…m node cáº§n xÃ³a
        if key > root.val:
            root.right = self.deleteNode(root.right, key)
            return root
        elif key < root.val:
            root.left = self.deleteNode(root.left, key)
            return root
        else:
            # TrÆ°á»ng há»£p xÃ³a node lÃ¡
            if not root.left and not root.right:
                return None
                        # TrÆ°á»ng há»£p xÃ³a node lÃ¡
            elif root.left and not root.right:
                return root.left
            elif root.right and not root.left:
                return root.right
            else:
                max_right_node = self.FindSmallestRight(root.right)
                root.val = max_right_node.val
                root.right = self.deleteNode(root.right, root.val)

        return root
```

## [Video tham kháº£o](https://leetcode.com/problems/maximum-depth-of-binary-tree/description/)  **`EASY`**

Given the root of a binary tree, return its maximum depth.

A binary tree's maximum depth is the number of nodes along the longest path from the root node down to the farthest leaf node.


```python
### Äá»‘i vá»›i bÃ i nÃ y thÃ¬ chÃºng ta sáº½ cÅ©ng sáº½ dÃ¹ng cÃ¡ch duyá»‡t (inverse) tá»« trÃªn xuá»‘ng dÆ°á»›i
### má»—i láº«n duyá»‡t chÃºng ta sáº½ cá»™ng Ä‘á»™ cao cá»§a cÃ¢y lÃªn 1. NgoÃ i ra chÃºng ta sáº½ duyá»‡t 2 nhÃ¡nh cá»§a
### root riÃªng (left , right) rá»“i tá»« Ä‘Ã³ so sÃ¡nh bÃªn nÃ o cÃ³ Ä‘á»™ cao lá»›n nháº¥t thÃ¬ láº¥y

class TreeNode:
    def __init__(self, val=0, left=None, right=None):
        self.val = val
        self.left = left
        self.right = right

class Solution:
    def maxDepth(self, root: Optional[TreeNode]) -> int:
        # Náº¿u ban Ä‘áº§u root lÃ  rá»—ng
        if root is None:

            return 0
        # Duyá»‡t cÃ¢y
        left = self.maxDepth(root.left)
        right = self.maxDepth(root.right)

        # Láº¥y max cá»§a 2 nhÃ¡nh trÃ¡i vÃ  pháº£i rá»“i sau Ä‘Ã³ cá»™ng thÃªm 1 lÃ  do Ä‘á»™ cao tá»« node root Ä‘áº¿n 2 nhÃ¡nh Ä‘Ã³ ná»¯a
        return max(left , right) + 1
```

## [Video tham kháº£o](https://leetcode.com/problems/path-sum/description/)  **`EASY`**

Given the root of a binary tree and an integer targetSum, return true if the tree has a root-to-leaf path such that adding up all the values along the path equals targetSum.

A leaf is a node with no children.


```python
### Äá» bÃ i yÃªu cáº§u lÃ  cÃ³ con Ä‘Æ°á»ng nÃ o Ä‘i tá»« root Ä‘áº¿n node lÃ¡ nÃ o cÃ³ tá»•ng nhÆ° dá» bÃ i yÃªu cáº§u khÃ´ng
### CÃ¡ch tiáº¿p cáº­n cÅ©ng chÃ­nh lÃ  sá»­ dá»¥ng duyá»‡t, khi node hiá»‡n táº¡i lÃ  None thÃ¬ sáº½ tiáº¿n hÃ nh kiá»…m tra
### Xem tá»•ng cá»§a nÃ³ cÃ³ báº±ng Ä‘á» bÃ i khÃ´ng


class TreeNode:
    def __init__(self, val=0, left=None, right=None):
        self.val = val
        self.left = left
        self.right = right

class Solution:
    # Táº­n dá»¥ng hÃ m má»¥c tiÃªu lÃ m hÃ m duyá»‡t luÃ´n
    def hasPathSum(self, root: Optional[TreeNode], targetSum: int) -> bool:

        # Náº¿u ban Ä‘áº§u root lÃ  None hoáº·c Ä‘Ã£ tá»›i node lÃ¡ rá»“i mÃ  khÃ´ng khÃ´ng tÃ¬m Ä‘Æ°á»£c
        # Ä‘Æ°á»ng Ä‘i thÃ¬ tráº£ vá» None luÃ´n
        if root is None:
            return False

        # Tá»›i Node lÃ¡ thÃ¬ kiá»…m tra cÃ³ tá»•ng Ä‘Æ°á»ng Ä‘i cÃ³ káº¿t quáº£ giá»‘ng vá»›i target
        # khÃ´ng
        if not root.left and not root.right:
            if root.val == targetSum:
                return True

        # XÃ©t theo 2 nhÃ¡nh
        left = self.hasPathSum(root.left, targetSum - root.val)
        right = self.hasPathSum(root.right, targetSum - root.val)

        return left or right
```

## [Video tham kháº£o](https://leetcode.com/problems/balanced-binary-tree/description/)  **`EASY`**

Given a binary tree, determine if it is height-balanced.


```python
### Äá»‘i vá»›i bÃ i nÃ y thÃ¬ chÃºng ta sáº½ táº­n dá»¥ng code cá»§a LEETCODE 104. Maximum Depth
### of Binary Tree cá»§a bÃ i trÃªn. ChÃºng ta sáº½ chá»‰nh sá»­a láº¡i má»™t xÃ­u Ä‘á»ƒ phÃ¹ há»£p vá»›i
### bÃ i toÃ¡n cá»§a chÃºng ta. Má»—i láº§n khi tÃ¬m Ä‘Æ°á»£c Ä‘á»™ cá»§a cá»§a left vÃ  right rá»“i chÃºng
### ta sáº½ tiáº¿n hÃ nh so sÃ¡nh Ä‘á»™ cao cá»§a 2 nhÃ¡nh Ä‘Ã³ náº¿u nÃ³ lá»›n hÆ¡n 1 thÃ¬ tráº£ vá»
### False

class TreeNode:
    def __init__(self, val=0, left=None, right=None):
        self.val = val
        self.left = left
        self.right = right

class Solution:
    # HÃ m há»• trá»£ tÃ¬m chiá»u cao cÃ¢y
    def height_compare(self, root: Optional[TreeNode]) -> int:
        # Náº¿u root lÃ  rá»—ng hoáº·c duyá»‡t háº¿t Node
        if root is None:
            return 0

        left = self.height_compare(root.left)
        right = self.height_compare(root.right)

        # Tiáº¿n hÃ nh so sanh chiá»u cao cá»§a 2 nhÃ¡nh hiá»‡n táº¡i
        if abs(left - right) > 1:
            return -1

        # TrÆ°á»ng há»£p cáº£ 2 nhÃ¡nh Ä‘iá»u -1 thÃ¬ max(-1, -1) + 1 sáº½ lÃ  0 nÃªn cáº§n pháº£i
        # return láº¡i ngay luÃ´n
        if left == -1 or right == -1:
            return - 1

        return max(left, right) + 1

    def isBalanced(self, root: Optional[TreeNode]) -> bool:
        return self.height_compare(root) != -1
```
